Yes =E2=80=94 *those sysfs commands create a continuous repeating PWM wavef=
orm*,
not a one=E2=80=91shot pulse.

Let me break it down in a clean, intuitive way so you can visualize exactly
what happens electrically.
------------------------------
=F0=9F=94=81 *Does this produce a continuous wave?*

echo 0 > /sys/class/pwm/pwmchip2/export
echo 20000000 > /sys/class/pwm/pwmchip2/pwm0/period
echo 1000000  > /sys/class/pwm/pwmchip2/pwm0/duty_cycle
echo 1 > /sys/class/pwm/pwmchip2/pwm0/enable

=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F *Yes =E2=80=94 this produces a continuous PWM waveform*

It repeats forever until you:

   - disable it
   - unexport it
   - or reboot

So the output looks like:

HIGH for 1 ms
LOW  for 19 ms
HIGH for 1 ms
LOW  for 19 ms
HIGH for 1 ms
LOW  for 19 ms
... repeating forever

This is a *20 ms period* (50 Hz) with *1 ms duty* (5%).
------------------------------
=F0=9F=A7=A0 *Why it repeats continuously*

PWM hardware is designed to generate a periodic signal:

   - The hardware timer reloads the period automatically
   - The duty cycle is applied every cycle
   - No CPU involvement after enabling

So once you write:

echo 1 > enable

the PWM controller starts running in hardware and keeps going.
------------------------------
=F0=9F=A7=A9 *Your question: =E2=80=9C7_7_7_7_7_7 or just one 7_?=E2=80=9D*=
 =E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F It is
*7_7_7_7_7_7_7_7_7...*

A repeating pattern.
=E2=9D=8C It is *not* a single pulse.

PWM =3D *continuous periodic waveform*.

If you wanted a *single pulse*, that requires a different mechanism (like a
one=E2=80=91shot timer or manually enabling/disabling PWM at precise times)=
.
------------------------------
=F0=9F=94=A7 If you want, I can also explain:

   - How to generate a *single pulse* using PWM
   - How to change duty/period dynamically
   - How to use PWM from a kernel driver instead of sysfs
   - How PWM interacts with pinctrl and clock frameworks

Just tell me where you want to go next.

